{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523617"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:57:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:57:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13912"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13912"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.36,0.2,0.11,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6531"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57002"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6531","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6531"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13912"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42451"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"761"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13069"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14082"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37479"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57002","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57002"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 39-year-old man is referred to the surgical clinic with increasing breathlessness and a chest X-ray showing an abnormality of the left hemidiaphragm. His symptoms have worsened as his weight has increased. He denies any recent trauma or surgery to the chest or neck region. He is otherwise fit and well. He does not take any regular medications and does not smoke. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The chest X-ray is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis based on this patient\u0027s chest X-ray?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Eventration of the diaphragm","Diaphragmatic hernia","Hiatus hernia","Parapneumonic effusion","Pleural effusion"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe chest X-ray shows colonic haustration in the left hemithorax, which is diagnostic of a \u003Cstrong\u003Ediaphragmatic hernia\u003C/strong\u003E. These types of hernias are usually congenital in origin and the defect is not at the oesophageal hiatus. The two types of congenital diaphragmatic hernia are Morgagni hernia and Bochdalek hernia. Acquired diaphragmatic hernias are usually associated with penetrating or blunt trauma. This patient\u0027s presentation of progressive dyspnoea, especially worsening with weight gain, is consistent with a diaphragmatic hernia that has been present since birth but has only become symptomatic in adulthood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEventration of the diaphragm\u003C/strong\u003E refers to an abnormal elevation of part of the diaphragm. While it can cause similar symptoms, it would not show bowel loops in the thoracic cavity on X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ehiatus hernia\u003C/strong\u003E involves protrusion of the stomach through the esophageal hiatus of the diaphragm. While it can cause respiratory symptoms, it typically does not present with colonic haustration in the chest X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParapneumonic effusion\u003C/strong\u003E is a fluid collection in the pleural space associated with pneumonia. It would appear as a homogeneous opacity on chest X-ray, not as bowel loops in the thorax.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPleural effusion\u003C/strong\u003E is an abnormal collection of fluid in the pleural space. Like a parapneumonic effusion, it would appear as a homogeneous opacity on chest X-ray, not as bowel loops.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt operation, this patient was found to have a Morgagni hernia, which is a type of congenital diaphragmatic hernia. The defect measured 10 cm and contained much of his stomach, transverse colon, and small bowel. The surgical approach involved extending a left thoracotomy into the right subcostal region to repair the defect. This case highlights that congenital diaphragmatic hernias can sometimes remain asymptomatic until adulthood, presenting with progressive respiratory symptoms as abdominal contents gradually herniate into the thoracic cavity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Diaphragmatic hernias can present with progressive dyspnoea, especially in adults with increasing weight.","Chest X-ray showing bowel loops in the thoracic cavity is diagnostic of a diaphragmatic hernia.","Morgagni hernia is a type of congenital diaphragmatic hernia that may not present until adulthood."],"references":["https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557501/#:~:text=Morgagni%20hernias%20are%20rare%20congenital,the%20chest%20or%20the%20abdomen."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42451"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13912"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20847"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20848"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20847"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/JTC2g4Jw7Yl41MBCEkuukIodoFDb5L.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/JTC2g4Jw7Yl41MBCEkuukIodoFDb5L.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1197}},{"type":"media","id":"20848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20848"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/m